# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: william-hulbert
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The **Great Chicago Fire** was a conflagration that burned in Chicago, Illinois, United States, during October 8–10, 1871.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The fire killed approximately 300 people, destroyed 17,000 structures across roughly 3.3 square miles (9 km2), and left more than 100,000 residents homeless.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The fire began in a neighborhood southwest of the city center.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] A long period of hot, dry, windy conditions, and the wooden construction prevalent in the city, led to the conflagration spreading quickly.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The fire leapt the south branch of the Chicago River and destroyed much of central Chicago and then crossed the main stem of the river, consuming the Near North Side.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Help flowed to the city from near and far after the fire.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The city government improved building codes to stop the rapid spread of future fires and rebuilt rapidly to those higher standards.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] A donation from the United Kingdom spurred the establishment of the Chicago Public Library.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] According to Nancy Connolly, great-great-granddaughter of Catherine O'Leary, the fire is said to have started at about 8:30 p.m. on October 8, in or around a small barn belonging to the O'Leary family that bordered the alley behind 137 W.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] DeKoven Street when Daniel "Peg-Leg" Sullivan accidentally knocked over a lantern while looking for beer for a party.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The shed next to the barn was the first building to be consumed by the fire.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] City officials never determined the cause of the blaze, but the rapid spread of the fire due to a long drought in that year's summer, strong winds from the southwest, and the rapid destruction of the water pumping system explain the extensive damage of the mainly wooden city structures.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] There has been much speculation over the years on the single start to the fire.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The most historically popular tale blames Mrs.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] O'Leary's cow, which allegedly knocked over a lantern; others state that a group of men were gambling inside the barn and knocked over a lantern.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Still other speculation suggests that the blaze was related to other fires in the Midwest that day.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] In 1997, the Chicago City Council formally exonerated O'Leary of any responsibility for the fire, following research by historian Richard Bales.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The fire's spread was aided by the city's use of wood as the predominant building material in a style called balloon frame.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] More than two-thirds of the structures in Chicago at the time of the fire were made entirely of wood, with most of the houses and buildings being topped with highly combustible tar or shingle roofs.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] All of the city's sidewalks and many roads were also made of wood.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Compounding this problem, Chicago received only 1 inch (25 mm) of rain from July 4 to October 9, causing severe drought conditions before the fire, while strong southwest winds helped to carry flying embers toward the heart of the city.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] In 1871, the Chicago Fire Department had 185 firefighters with just 17 horse-drawn steam pumpers to protect the entire city.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The initial response by the fire department was timely, but due to an error by the watchman, Mathias Schaffer, the firefighters were initially sent to the wrong place, allowing the fire to grow unchecked.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] An alarm sent from the area near the fire also failed to register at the courthouse where the fire watchmen were, while the firefighters were tired from having fought numerous small fires and one large fire in the week before.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] These factors combined to turn a small barn fire into a conflagration.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] When firefighters finally arrived at DeKoven Street, the fire had grown and spread to neighboring buildings and was progressing toward the central business district.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Firefighters had hoped that the South Branch of the Chicago River and an area that had previously thoroughly burned would act as a natural firebreak.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] All along the river, however, were lumber yards, warehouses, and coal yards, as well as barges, and numerous bridges across the river.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] As the fire grew, the southwest wind intensified and the temperature rose, causing structures to catch fire from the heat and from burning debris blown by the wind.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Around midnight, flaming debris blew across the river and landed on roofs and the South Side Gas Works.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] With the fire across the river and moving rapidly toward the heart of the city, panic set in.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Mason sent messages to nearby towns asking for help.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] When the courthouse caught fire, he ordered the building to be evacuated and the prisoners jailed in the basement to be released.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] At 2:30 a.m. on the 9th, the cupola of the courthouse collapsed, sending the great bell crashing down.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Some witnesses reported hearing the sound from a mile (1.6 km) away.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] As more buildings succumbed to the flames, a major contributing factor to the fire's spread was a meteorological phenomenon known as a fire whirl.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] As hot air rises, it comes into contact with cooler air and begins to spin, creating a tornado-like effect.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] These fire whirls are likely what drove flaming debris so high and so far.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Such debris was blown across the main branch of the Chicago River to a railroad car carrying kerosene.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The fire had jumped the river a second time and was now raging across the city's north side.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Despite the fire spreading and growing rapidly, the city's firefighters continued to battle the blaze.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] A short time after the fire jumped the river, a burning piece of timber lodged on the roof of the city's waterworks.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Within minutes, the interior of the building was engulfed in flames and the building was destroyed.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] With it, the city's water mains went dry and the city was helpless.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Contemporary Chicago Tribune reporting confirmed that the waterworks roof caught fire at an early hour, forcing firefighters to retreat before the building was lost.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The fire burned unchecked from building to building, block to block.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] One eyewitness account, reprinted from a Western paper, described a family trapped on the fourth floor of a building at the corner of Randolph and Market Streets, the father throwing his wife and children to safety below before collapsing beside his wife as the flames closed in.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Late in the evening of October 9, it started to rain, but the fire had already started to burn itself out.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The fire had spread to the sparsely populated areas of the north side, having thoroughly consumed the densely populated areas.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Once the fire had ended, the smoldering remains were still too hot for a survey of the damage to be completed for many days.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Eventually, the city determined that the fire destroyed an area about 4 miles (6 km) long and averaging 3⁄4 mile (1 km) wide, encompassing an area of more than 2,000 acres (809 ha).
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Destroyed were more than 73 miles (117 km) of roads, 120 miles (190 km) of sidewalk, 2,000 lampposts, 17,500 buildings, and $222 million in property, which was about a third of the city's valuation in 1871.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Sheridan's command structure consisted of a mix of regular troops, militia units, police, and a specially organized civilian group "First Regiment of Chicago Volunteers".
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Former Lieutenant-Governor William Bross, and part owner of the *Tribune*, later recollected his response to the arrival of Gen.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Sheridan and his soldiers: "Never did deeper emotions of joy overcome me.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Thank God, those most dear to me and the city as well are safe." For two weeks, Sheridan's men patrolled the streets, guarded the relief warehouses, and enforced other regulations.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] On October 24 the troops were relieved of their duties and the volunteers were mustered out of service.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Of the approximately 324,000 inhabitants of Chicago in 1871, 90,000 Chicago residents (about 28% of the population) were left homeless.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] 120 bodies were recovered, but the death toll may have been as high as 300.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The county coroner speculated that an accurate count was impossible, as some victims may have drowned or had been incinerated, leaving no remains.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] In the days and weeks following the fire, monetary donations flowed into Chicago from around the country and abroad, along with donations of food, clothing, and other goods.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] These donations came from individuals, corporations, and cities.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] New York City gave $450,000 (equivalent to $12.1 million today) along with clothing and provisions, St.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Louis gave $300,000 (equivalent to $8.06 million today), and the Common Council of London gave 1,000 guineas, as well as £7,000 from private donations.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] 40,000) a town meeting raised £518 on the spot.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Cincinnati, Cleveland, and Buffalo, all commercial rivals, donated hundreds and thousands of dollars.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Milwaukee, along with other nearby cities, helped by sending fire-fighting equipment.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Food, clothing and books were brought by train from all over the continent.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Mayor Mason placed the Chicago Relief and Aid Society in charge of the city's relief efforts.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Operating from the First Congregational Church, city officials and aldermen began taking steps to preserve order in Chicago.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Price gouging was a key concern, and in one ordinance, the city set the price of bread at 8¢ for a 12-ounce (340 g) loaf.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Public buildings were opened as places of refuge, and saloons closed at 9 in the evening for the week following the fire.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Many people who were left homeless after the incident were never able to get their normal lives back since all their personal papers and belongings burned in the conflagration.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Tribune reporting also documented deliberate arson during the chaos: one man set fire to the Jesuit Church on the West Side, while a woman was arrested for firing a building on Burnside Street; the man was caught by neighbors, stoned, and beaten to death on the spot.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Burgess of London proposed an "English Book Donation", to spur a free library in Chicago, in their sympathy with Chicago over the damages suffered.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Libraries in Chicago had been private with membership fees.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] In April 1872, the City Council passed the ordinance to establish the free Chicago Public Library, starting with the donation from the United Kingdom of more than 8,000 volumes.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The fire also led to questions about development in the United States.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Due to Chicago's rapid expansion at that time, the fire led to Americans reflecting on industrialization.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Based on a religious point of view, some said that Americans should return to a more old-fashioned way of life, and that the fire was caused by people ignoring traditional morality.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] On the other hand, others believed that a lesson to be learned from the fire was that cities needed to improve their building techniques.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Olmsted also believed that with brick walls, and disciplined firemen and police, the deaths and damage caused would have been much less.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Almost immediately, the city began to rewrite its fire standards, spurred by the efforts of leading insurance executives, and fire-prevention reformers such as Arthur C.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Chicago soon developed one of the country's leading fire-fighting forces.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Business owners and land speculators such as Gurdon Saltonstall Hubbard quickly set about rebuilding the city.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The first load of lumber for rebuilding was delivered the day the last burning building was extinguished.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] By the World's Columbian Exposition 22 years later, Chicago hosted more than 21 million visitors.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The Palmer House hotel burned to the ground in the fire 13 days after its grand opening.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Its developer, Potter Palmer, secured a loan and rebuilt the hotel to higher standards, across the street from the original, proclaiming it to be "The World's First Fireproof Building".
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] In 1956, the remaining structures on the original O'Leary property at 558 W.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] DeKoven Street were torn down for construction of the Chicago Fire Academy, a training facility for Chicago firefighters, known as the Quinn Fire Academy or Chicago Fire Department Training Facility.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] A bronze sculpture of stylized flames, entitled *Pillar of Fire* by Egon Weiner, was erected on the point of origin in 1961.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Michael's Church and the Pumping Station were both gutted in the fire, but their exteriors survived, and the buildings were rebuilt using the surviving walls.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Additionally, though the inhabitable portions of the building were destroyed, the bell tower of St.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] James Cathedral survived the fire and was incorporated into the rebuilt church.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The stones near the top of the tower are still blackened from the soot and smoke.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Almost from the moment the fire broke out, various theories about its cause began to circulate.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The most popular and enduring legend maintains that the fire began in the O'Leary barn as Mrs.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The cow kicked over a lantern (or an oil lamp in some versions), setting fire to the barn.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The O'Leary family denied this, stating that they were in bed before the fire started, but stories of the cow began to spread across the city.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Catherine O'Leary seemed the perfect scapegoat: she was a poor, Irish Catholic immigrant.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] During the latter half of the 19th century, anti-Irish sentiment was strong in Chicago and throughout the United States.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] This was intensified as a result of the growing political power of the city's Irish population.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Furthermore, the United States had been distrustful of Catholics (or papists, as they were often called) since its beginning, carrying over attitudes in England in the 17th century; as an Irish Catholic, Mrs.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] O'Leary was a target of both anti-Catholic and anti-Irish sentiment.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] This story was circulating in Chicago even before the flames had died out, and it was noted in the *Chicago Tribune'*s first post-fire issue.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] In 1893 the reporter Michael Ahern retracted the "cow-and-lantern" story, admitting it was fabricated, but even his confession was unable to put the legend to rest.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Although the O'Learys were never officially charged with starting the fire, the story became so engrained in local lore that Chicago's city council officially exonerated them—and the cow—in 1997.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Amateur historian Richard Bales has suggested the fire started when Daniel "Pegleg" Sullivan, who first reported the fire, ignited hay in the barn while trying to steal milk.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Bales's account does not have consensus.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The Chicago Public Library staff criticized his account in their web page on the fire.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Despite this, the Chicago city council was convinced of Bales's argument and stated that the actions of Sullivan on that day should be scrutinized after the O'Leary family was exonerated in 1997.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Anthony DeBartolo reported evidence in two articles of the *Chicago Tribune* (October 8, 1997, and March 3, 1998, reprinted in *Hyde Park Media*) suggesting that Louis M.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Cohn may have started the fire during a craps game.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Following his death in 1942, Cohn bequeathed $35,000 which was assigned by his executors to the Medill School of Journalism at Northwestern University.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The bequest was given to the school on September 28, 1944, and the dedication contained a claim by Cohn to have been present at the start of the fire.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] According to Cohn, on the night of the fire, he was gambling in the O'Learys' barn with one of their sons and some other neighborhood boys.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] O'Leary came out to the barn to chase the gamblers away at around 9:00, they knocked over a lantern in their flight, although Cohn states that he paused long enough to scoop up the money.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The argument is not universally accepted.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] An alternative theory, first suggested in 1882 by Ignatius L.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Donnelly in *Ragnarok: The Age of Fire and Gravel*, is that the fire was caused by a meteor shower.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] This was described as a "fringe theory" concerning Biela's Comet.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] At a 2004 conference of the Aerospace Corporation and the American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics, engineer and physicist Robert Wood suggested that the fire began when a fragment of Biela's Comet impacted the Midwest.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Biela's Comet had broken apart in 1845 and had not been observed since.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Wood argued that four large fires took place, all on the same day, all on the shores of Lake Michigan (see related events), suggesting a common root cause.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Eyewitnesses reported sighting spontaneous ignitions, lack of smoke, "balls of fire" falling from the sky, and blue flames.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] According to Wood, these accounts suggest that the fires were caused by the methane that is commonly found in comets.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Meteorites are not known to start or spread fires and are cool to the touch after reaching the ground, so this theory has not found favor in the scientific community.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Methane-air mixtures become flammable only when the methane concentration exceeds 5%, at which point the mixtures also become explosive, a situation unlikely to occur from meteorites.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Methane gas is lighter than air and thus does not accumulate near the ground; any localized pockets of methane in the open air rapidly dissipate.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Moreover, if a fragment of an icy comet were to strike the Earth, the most likely outcome, due to the low tensile strength of such bodies, would be for it to disintegrate in the upper atmosphere, leading to a meteor air burst like the Tunguska event.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The specific choice of Biela's Comet does not match with the dates in question, as the 6-year period of the comet's orbit did not intersect that of the Earth until 1872, one full year after the fire, when a large meteor shower was observed.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] A common cause for the fires in the Midwest in late 1871 is that the area had had a dry summer, so that winds from the front that moved in that evening were capable of generating rapidly expanding blazes from available ignition sources, which were plentiful in the region.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] On that hot, dry, and windy autumn day, three other major fires occurred along the shores of Lake Michigan at the same time as the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Some 250 miles (400 km) to the north, the Peshtigo Fire consumed the town of Peshtigo, Wisconsin, along with a dozen other villages.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] It killed 1,200 to 2,500 people and charred approximately 1.5 million acres (6,100 km2).
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The Peshtigo Fire remains the deadliest in American history but the remoteness of the region meant it was little noticed at the time, because one of the first things that burned were the telegraph lines to Green Bay.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Across the lake to the east, the town of Holland, Michigan, and other nearby areas burned to the ground.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Some 100 miles (160 km) to the north of Holland, the lumbering community of Manistee also went up in flames in what became known as the Great Michigan Fire.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Farther east, along the shore of Lake Huron, the Port Huron Fire swept through Port Huron, Michigan and much of Michigan's "Thumb".
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] On October 9, 1871, a fire swept through the city of Urbana, Illinois, 140 miles (230 km) south of Chicago, destroying portions of its downtown area.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] Windsor, Ontario, likewise burned on October 12.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] The town of Singapore, Michigan, provided a large portion of the lumber to rebuild Chicago.
[src:william-hulbert/1871-great-chicago-fire] As a result, Singapore was so heavily deforested that the land deteriorated into barren sand dunes that buried the town, which had to be abandoned.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The **1877 Louisville Grays scandal** was an incident in which members of the Louisville Grays baseball team accepted money to lose games.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Four players – Bill Craver, Jim Devlin, George Hall and Al Nichols – were subsequently banned from professional baseball for life.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In the early days of professional baseball, crooked play was not uncommon, and many players were suspected of throwing games in exchange for money.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Illegal influence by gamblers had undermined the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) in the early 1870s, and William Hulbert formed the National League (NL) in 1876 with the intention of driving it out of the game.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nevertheless, there were still several gambling-related scandals during the 1876 season.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Jim Devlin started his baseball career in 1873 and was the Louisville Grays' pitcher in 1876 and 1877.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1876 he had a win–loss record of 30–35 and an earned run average of 1.56, while leading the league in complete games, innings pitched and strikeouts.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, Devlin went 35–25 with a 2.25 ERA and again led the league in complete games and innings pitched.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started and completed each of the Grays' 61 games, an accomplishment no other pitcher in history has matched.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Outfielder George Hall was one of the best sluggers in the game's early history.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After playing in the NA from 1871 to 1875, he joined the Philadelphia Athletics in 1876.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] That season, he led the league with five home runs and finished second in batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage and total bases.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, he played for the Grays and had a .323 batting average.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Shortstop Bill Craver was a noted crooked player who had been expelled from a previous team for throwing games in 1870.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He played for the New York Mutuals in 1876 before joining the Grays the following season.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Al Nichols also played for the Mutuals in 1876.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He joined the Grays in the middle of the 1877 season on the recommendation of Hall and appeared in six games for the team.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Newspapers named the players "Terror" Devlin, "Gentleman George" Hall, "Butcher" Craver and "Slippery Elm" Nichols".
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After the games of August 13, 1877, the Grays were in first place by four games over St.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louis and 4.5 over the Boston Red Caps, with a record of 27 wins and 13 losses, and with some 20 games left to play.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They then commenced a nine-game winless streak (including one tie) and eventually lost the championship to Boston.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They won six out of their last seven, making their season record of 35-25 look reasonably respectable, but those wins came after Boston had clinched the pennant, having won 20 of their final 21 games.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louisville finished second, seven games behind Boston.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Chase received telegrams informing him of suspicious gambling activity involving the team.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started an investigation, and Devlin and Hall confessed to throwing several exhibition games late in the season, with Devlin receiving up to $100 per game.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 4, the entire team was gathered, and Chase demanded that they turn over their telegrams.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Every player except Craver complied, and the telegrams showed that Devlin, Hall and Nichols had thrown games.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 30, Craver, Devlin, Hall and Nichols were expelled from the club, and on December 4, the NL banned them from professional baseball for the rest of their lives.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The Grays franchise folded after the 1877 season.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Over the next few decades, there were fewer suspicions of game-fixing in professional baseball.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The four banned players were never reinstated.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nichols played semi-professional baseball, Craver and Devlin became police officers, and Hall worked as an engraver and clerk.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Devlin tried to be reinstated many times but was unsuccessful.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In one instance, he got on his knees and begged Hulbert for another chance.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Hulbert responded by handing him $50 (roughly equivalent to $1,200 in 2017 value) and saying, "Devlin, that's what I think of you personally; but, damn you, you have sold a game; you are dishonest and this National League will not stand for it." Devlin died of tuberculosis in 1883.
[src:william-hulbert/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] His 1.90 career ERA is the third-lowest of all-time among pitchers with at least 1,000 innings pitched.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Elections to the Baseball Hall of Fame for 1995 introduced a system of multiple classified ballots for consideration by the Veterans Committee.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] That group met in closed sessions as usual and selected four people: Richie Ashburn, Leon Day, William Hulbert, and Vic Willis.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Day and Hulbert were named from the new ballots for Negro leagues and 19th century figures.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The Baseball Writers' Association of America (BBWAA) voted by mail, per their usual process, to select from recent major league players; they elected Mike Schmidt.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] A formal induction ceremony was held in Cooperstown, New York, on July 30, 1995.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The BBWAA was authorized to elect players active in 1975 or later, but not after 1989; the ballot included candidates from the 1994 ballot who received at least 5% of the vote but were not elected, along with selected players, chosen by a screening committee, whose last appearance was in 1990.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] All 10-year members of the BBWAA were eligible to vote.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Voters were instructed to cast votes for up to 10 candidates; any candidate receiving votes on at least 75% of the ballots would be honored with induction to the Hall.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The ballot consisted of 39 players; a total of 460 ballots were cast, with 345 votes required for election.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] A total of 2,829 individual votes were cast, an average of 6.15 per ballot.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Those candidates receiving less than 5% of the vote (23 votes) will not appear on future BBWAA ballots, but may eventually be considered by the Veterans Committee.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Candidates who were eligible for the first time are indicated here with a dagger (†).
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The one candidate who received at least 75% of the vote and was elected is indicated in ***bold italics***; candidates who have since been elected in subsequent elections are indicated in *italics*.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The 14 candidates who received less than 5% of the vote, thus becoming ineligible for future BBWAA consideration, are indicated with an asterisk (*).
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Thurman Munson was on the ballot for the 15th and final time.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The newly eligible players included 24 All-Stars, eleven of whom were not included on the ballot, representing a total of 67 All-Star selections.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Among the new candidates were 12-time All-Star Mike Schmidt, 8-time All-Star Jim Rice and 5-time All-Star Buddy Bell.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The field included three MVPs (Schmidt, Rice and Willie Hernández) and one Cy Young Award winner (Hernández).
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] In addition to Schmidt, Phillies broadcaster and former center fielder Richie Ashburn was inducted to the hall by the Veteran's Committee.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Phillie fans were elated over the results, and came to Cooperstown that July in droves.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The Veterans Committee met in closed sessions to elect as many as two executives, managers, umpires, and older major league players—the categories considered in all its meetings since 1953.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] By a new arrangement it separately considered candidates from the Negro leagues and from the 19th century with authority to select one from each of those two special ballots.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The committee elected four people, the maximum number permitted: center fielder Richie Ashburn from the 1950s, pitcher Vic Willis from the 1900s, pitcher Leon Day from the Negro leagues, and from the 19th century William Hulbert, the founder and second president of the National League.
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] There was no Spink Award to a baseball writer in 1995 (none voted at the December 1994 meeting at the BBWAA).
[src:william-hulbert/1995-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Frick Award honoring a baseball broadcaster.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Giamatti served as Commissioner for only five months before dying suddenly of a heart attack.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] He is the shortest-tenured baseball commissioner in the sport's history and the only holder of the office not to preside over a full Major League Baseball season.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Giamatti's most notable act as Commissioner was to negotiate the agreement resolving the Pete Rose betting scandal in which Rose was permitted to voluntarily withdraw from the sport to avoid further punishment.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Giamatti was born in Boston and grew up in South Hadley, Massachusetts, the son of Mary Claybaugh Walton (Smith College, 1935) and Valentine John Giamatti.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] His father was professor and chairman of the Department of Italian Language and Literature at Mount Holyoke College.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Giamatti's paternal grandparents were Italian immigrants Angelo Giammattei (Italian pronunciation: [dʒammatˈtɛi]) and Maria Lavorgna (Italian pronunciation: [laˈvɔrɲa; -orɲa]): his grandfather Angelo emigrated to the United States from Telese, near Benevento, Italy, around 1900.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Giamatti's maternal grandparents, from Wakefield, Massachusetts, were Helen Buffum (Davidson) and Bartlett Walton, who graduated from Phillips Academy Andover and Harvard College.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Giamatti attended South Hadley High School, spent his junior year at the American Overseas School of Rome, and graduated from Phillips Academy in 1956.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] At Yale College, he was a member of Delta Kappa Epsilon (Phi chapter) and as a junior in 1960 was tapped by Scroll and Key, a senior secret society.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] In 1960, he married Toni Marilyn Smith, who taught English for more than 20 years at the Hopkins School in New Haven, Connecticut, until her death in 2004.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Together the couple had three children: actors Paul and Marcus and jewelry designer Elena.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Giamatti stayed in New Haven to receive his doctorate in 1964, when he also published a volume of essays by Thomas G.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Bergin he had co-edited with a philosophy graduate student, T.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] He became a professor of comparative literature at Yale University, an author, and master of Ezra Stiles College at Yale, a post to which he was appointed by his predecessor as Yale president, Kingman Brewster Jr.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Giamatti taught briefly at Princeton but spent most of his academic life at Yale.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] His scholarly work focused on English Renaissance literature, particularly Edmund Spenser, and relationships between English and Italian Renaissance poets.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] His tenure as Stiles master ended in 1972.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Giamatti served as president of Yale University from 1978 to 1986.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] He was the youngest president of the university in its history and presided over the university during a bitter strike by its clerical and technical workers in 1984–1985.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] As university president, he refused student, faculty, and community demands to divest from apartheid South Africa.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Giamatti prohibited students from playing Bladderball on campus after years of increasingly strange pranks and several student hospitalizations in 1982.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] He also served on the board of trustees of Mount Holyoke College for many years.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Giamatti was elected a fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1980 and a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1982.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Giamatti had a lifelong interest in baseball and was a noted Boston Red Sox fan.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Giamatti was named president of the National League in 1986.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] During his stint in that position, he placed an emphasis on the need to improve the environment for the fan in the ballparks.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] He also decided to make umpires strictly enforce the balk rule and cited affirmative action as a remedy for the lack of minority managers, coaches, or executives in the major leagues.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] While still serving as National League president, Giamatti suspended Pete Rose for 30 games after Rose shoved umpire Dave Pallone on April 30, 1988.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Later that year, Giamatti also suspended Los Angeles Dodgers pitcher Jay Howell for three days, after Howell was caught using pine tar during the National League Championship Series.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Giamatti, whose tough dealing with Yale's union favorably impressed Major League Baseball owners, was unanimously elected to succeed Peter Ueberroth as commissioner on September 8, 1988.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] He formally took office on April 1, 1989.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Determined to maintain the integrity of the game, on August 24, 1989, Giamatti prevailed upon Pete Rose to agree voluntarily to remain permanently ineligible to play baseball.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] While at his vacation home in Edgartown on Martha's Vineyard, Giamatti, a heavy smoker for many years, died suddenly of a heart attack at the age of 51, eight days after banishing Pete Rose and 154 days into his tenure as commissioner.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] He was interred at Grove Street Cemetery in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] He became the second baseball commissioner to die in office, the first being Kenesaw Mountain Landis in 1944.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Fay Vincent, Giamatti's close friend and baseball's first deputy commissioner, became acting commissioner upon Giamatti's death, and was quickly elected by MLB owners to succeed Giamatti as the new commissioner.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] On October 14, 1989, before Game 1 at the World Series, Giamatti—to whom this World Series was dedicated—was memorialized with a moment of silence.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Son Marcus Giamatti threw out the first pitch before the game.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Also before Game One, the Yale Whiffenpoofs sang the national anthem, a blend of "The Star-Spangled Banner" with "America the Beautiful" that has been since repeated by other a cappella groups.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] The Little League Eastern Regional Headquarters in Bristol, Connecticut is named after Giamatti.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] One of the three awards given annually by Major League Baseball's Baseball Assistance Program is named the "Bart Giamatti Award".
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Giamatti was inducted into the National Italian American Sports Hall of Fame in 1992.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] James Reston Jr. notes in his book *Collision at Home Plate: The Lives of Pete Rose and Bart Giamatti* that Giamatti suffered from Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease, an inherited neuromuscular disease affecting peripheral nerves.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Neil Thomas Proto argues in his book *Fearless: A.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] Bartlett Giamatti and the Battle for Fairness* that Giamatti's early life with his parents and family in New Haven established the code of conduct about fairness that tempered his decision about Pete Rose.
[src:william-hulbert/a-bartlett-giamatti] The research library at the National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum is named in his honor.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Mills was born on March 12, 1844, in New York City, and lived there until September 1862, when he enlisted in the United States Army.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] He served briefly as a private in the 5th New York Volunteer Infantry before mustering as a Sergeant in the 165th New York Infantry Regiment, considered a sister-regiment to the 5th New York Infantry.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] While in the service, Mills continued to play baseball and later recalled that he would always pack his bat and ball along with his field equipment.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] He participated in a well-attended Christmas Day baseball game at Hilton Head Island, South Carolina in 1862 between the 165th New York Volunteer Infantry and nine other soldiers from other Union Army regiments.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] A reported 40,000 soldiers were in attendance.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] In 1864, Mills was promoted 2nd Lieutenant, before being honorably discharged at Charleston, South Carolina on September 1 1865.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] After the Civil War, Mills became a veteran companion of the Military Order of the Loyal Legion of the United States as Companion No.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] 07469; and a member of the Grand Army of the Republic.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] He wears medals of both organizations in the photograph shown here.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] After the war, Mills enrolled in Columbian Law School (now George Washington University) in Washington, D.C. to study law.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] While in Washington, Mills presided over the Olympic Base Ball Club for which he was also an occasional player.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] During his tenure, Mills tried unsuccessfully to recruit a young pitcher, Albert Spalding, whose career he would later come to influence.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] In 1872 Mills married Mary Chester Steele, and the couple had three daughters.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] After being admitted to the bar in 1876, he relocated his family to Chicago, Illinois where his career took an unexpected turn.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] During the late 19th century, it was common practice for professional leagues (such as the National League) to sign players already under contract with non-league teams.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Usually, several teammates were recruited together, forcing the depleted non-league team to disband.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Mills attacked the questionable ethics of the practice in a newspaper article and outlined a plan to prevent the raiding of non-league teams.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] William Hulbert, then president of the NL, noticed the article and solicited Mills for his advice on drafting an official solution, which resulted in the "League Alliance" (1877).
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Mills' contribution impressed the league, and he was hired on as an advisor.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Following Hulbert's death in 1882, the league unanimously elected him president.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Mills' primary objective as president sought to prevent players from switching from one professional league to the next, which they typically did during mid-season in search of higher salaries.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Unsurprisingly, the agreement was unpopular with players, who organized to form a new league for the 1884 season, the Union Association, which did not recognize the reserve rule or salary limitations.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Mills reacted by threatening the defecting players with permanent expulsion and heavy fines, but many chose to leave anyway.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Unfortunately, heavy financial losses and low attendance caused the UA and several participant teams to fold only after one season.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] UA players later attempted to rejoin the NL, but Mills was particularly adamant about sticking to his word.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] In spite of Mills' objections, the league saw opportunity for boosting profits, and voted to allow the former UA players back in.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] In 1884, Mills resigned as league president, frustrated by yet another humiliating defeat of principle when Henry Lucas—none other than the founder of the UA—was voted back into the league as owner of a new St.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] However, Mills continued to serve as an unofficial consultant on league matters.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] In 1888, Spalding accompanied a group of star players on a world tour to promote the game of baseball, playing an exhibition game in the shadow of the Great Pyramids of Egypt.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Upon their return the following year, a dinner was held to honor the players and Mills was asked to serve as master of ceremonies.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] The dinner, held at Delmonico's Restaurant in New York, was attended by an eclectic and prestigious crowd of 300 guests, among them Mark Twain and Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] The event's main theme focused on the sport as America's ambassador to the world.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Also emphasized was the notion that baseball had not, as many believed, evolved from the British game of rounders.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Reportedly, at various points throughout the evening, audience members broke out into rousing chants of "No rounders!
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] The display of patriotism intrigued Spalding and inspired a debate concerning baseball's origins, which came to a head in 1903 when Henry Chadwick published a widely read article for its part tracing baseball's evolution from rounders.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] In response, Spalding, who believed baseball was a fundamentally American invention, published an article disputing Chadwick's claim and challenged him by suggesting that they appoint a commission to settle the matter.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Chadwick agreed, and in 1905 a commission headed by Mills was formed.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] The "Mills Commission" featured Mills and six other prominent men: Morgan G.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Bulkeley, the NL's first president in 1876; Arthur P.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Gorman, a former player and ex-president of the Washington Base Ball Club; Nicholas E.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Young, the first secretary and fifth president (replacing Mills) of the NL; Alfred J.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Reach and George Wright, well known sporting goods distributors and two of the most famous players of their day; and James Edward Sullivan, president of the Amateur Athletic Union.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] The commission, through a series of nationally distributed publications, requested any American who had any knowledge concerning the origins of baseball to come forward.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] A number of circumstantial inconsistencies suggested that Graves' story was most likely fabricated.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Despite all of the unanswered questions, Mills wrote a memo known as the "Mills Commission Report" that proclaimed Doubleday the inventor of the game of baseball.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] For over half a century prior to coming under the scrutiny of historians, it remained the authoritative document on the issue.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] However, it is now accepted that Chadwick was correct in his belief that baseball had in fact evolved from the game of rounders.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Mills himself may have had some doubts concerning the validity of his own commission's findings and he admitted that he had had no conclusive evidence to prove the Doubleday claim.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] The commission was Mills' last major role in professional baseball.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] Having long spent his career working for the Hale Elevator Company of Chicago, Mills became vice-president of one of its agents—the Otis Elevator Company—in 1898 and held the position until his death.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] In his later years, Mills was involved in amateur athletics, becoming the director and president of the New York Athletic Club and in 1921, penned the American Olympic Association constitution.
[src:william-hulbert/abraham-g-mills] At the time of his death in 1929 in Falmouth, Massachusetts, he presided over the Association for the Protection of the Adirondacks, and was involved in planning the 1932 Winter Olympics.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss was born and raised in Wisconsin, where he attended St.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Mary's College (later part of Wyalusing Academy) in Prairie du Chien and the University of Wisconsin.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Mary's and then played in a semipro league where he caught the attention of Connie Mack.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss did not sign with Mack's team, but he attracted further major league interest after winning 19 games in 1900 for the Toledo Mud Hens.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss had another strong season for Toledo in 1901.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] After an offseason contract dispute between Joss, Toledo and Cleveland, he debuted with the Cleveland club in April 1902.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss led the league in shutouts that year.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] By 1905, Joss had completed the first of his four consecutive 20-win seasons.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Off the field, Joss worked as a newspaper sportswriter from 1906 until his death.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] In 1908, he pitched a perfect game during a tight pennant race that saw Cleveland finish a half-game out of first place; it was the closest that Joss came to a World Series berth.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] The 1910 season was his last, and Joss missed most of the year due to injury.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] In April 1911, Joss became ill and he died the same month due to tuberculous meningitis.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He finished his career with 160 wins, 234 complete games, 45 shutouts and 920 strikeouts.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Addie Joss was born on April 12, 1880, in Woodland, Dodge County, Wisconsin.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] His parents Jacob and Theresa (née Staudenmeyer) were farmers; his father, a cheesemaker who was involved in local politics, had emigrated from Switzerland.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] A heavy drinker of alcohol, he died from liver complications in 1890, when Joss was 10 years old; Joss remained sober throughout his life as a result of his father's death.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss attended elementary school in Juneau and Portage and high school at Wayland Academy in Beaver Dam, Wisconsin.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] By age 16 he finished high school and began teaching himself.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He was offered a scholarship to attend St.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Mary's College (also known as Sacred Heart College) in Watertown, where he played on the school's baseball team.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He also attended the University of Wisconsin (now University of Wisconsin–Madison), where he studied engineering.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Officials in Watertown were impressed with the quality of play of St.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Mary's and put the team on a semipro circuit.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] During his time on the semipro circuit, Joss employed his unique pitching windup, which involved hiding the ball until the very last moment in his delivery.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Connie Mack also sent a scout to watch Joss and later offered the young pitcher a job playing on his Albany club in the Western League, which Joss declined.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] In 1899, Joss played for a team in Oshkosh, earning $10 per week ($387 in today's dollars).
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] After player salaries were frozen by team owners, Joss joined the junior team in Manitowoc, which had been split into two teams, as a second baseman and was soon promoted to the senior squad, where he was developed into a pitcher.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He was seen by a scout for the Toledo Mud Hens and in 1900 accepted a position with the team for $75 per month ($2,903).
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] While in Ohio he was considered "the best amateur pitcher in the state." He started the Mud Hens' season opener on April 28 and earned the win in the team's 16–8 victory.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Midway through the 1901 season, the Boston Americans of the upstart American League offered $1,500 ($58,050) to Toledo to buy out Joss's contract.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Louis Cardinals of the National League (NL) matched Boston's offer; Toledo rejected both offers.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss continued to pitch for the Mud Hens and by the end of the 1901 season he had won 27 games and had 216 strikeouts (some sources say 25 games).
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] After the season ended, Joss returned to Wisconsin where he led Racine to the 1901 Wisconsin baseball state championship against Rube Waddell's Kenosha squad.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He also enrolled at Beloit College and played American football.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] It was reported that Joss had signed with the Brooklyn Dodgers of the National League as early as August 18 and received a $400 advance ($15,480), but Joss denied receiving any money.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Mud Hens owner Charles Stroebel stated that he had signed Joss and other Mud Hens players for the 1902 season on August 12 and that the Western League was under the protection of the National League through September 1901.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Before 1901 ended, the Cleveland Bronchos offered $500 ($19,350) to Toledo in exchange for Joss and manager Bob Gilks, who would be a scout for Cleveland.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Toledo and Joss agreed and Joss was now a member of the American League, which was paying a premium on baseball talent to rival the National League.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Dodgers owner Charles Ebbets invited Joss for a meeting, which Joss declined, and Joss let it be known that he had told Stroebel he would play for the Mud Hens for the 1902 season, and received a $150 ($5,582) advance in February 1902.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] In March 1902, Joss signed with Cleveland.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] For not returning the entire advance, Joss was charged with a felony and Stroebel pursued legal action.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss made his major league debut with the Bronchos on April 26, and two days later he arrived in Toledo to turn himself in, accompanied by Bronchos majority owner Charles Somers, who was also American League vice president.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Stroebel also filed a civil suit against the Bronchos, stating that his business had been interfered with, but Stroebel agreed to withdraw his charges in July when he accepted Bronchos pitcher Jack Lundbom.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss made his major league debut with the Cleveland Bronchos (also known as the Bluebirds) against the St.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] The Browns' Jesse Burkett hit a shallow pop fly in the direction of right fielder Zaza Harvey.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Home plate umpire Bob Caruthers ruled that Harvey did not make a clean catch, so Burkett was credited with a hit.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] (Harvey and witnesses said the ball never hit the ground.) Joss finished his major league debut with a one-hitter.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss compiled a 17–13 record and 2.77 ERA during his major league rookie season.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He led the American League with five shutouts.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] On October 11, 1902, Joss married Lillian Shinivar in Monroe, Michigan.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Shinivar was in attendance when Joss made his professional debut with the Mud Hens in 1900.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] The couple had a son, Norman, and a daughter, Ruth.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Following the conclusion of the 1902 season, Joss was selected to the All-Americans, an all-star team from the American League who played exhibition games against their counterparts from the National League.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] To begin the 1903 season, the Cleveland organization changed the team's name to the "Naps" in honor of second baseman Nap Lajoie.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] In Joss' second year, he went 18–13 and lowered his ERA from the season before to 2.19.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] His walks plus hits per inning pitched (WHIP) was an MLB-low 0.948.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] For the 1904 season, the 24-year-old Joss went 14–10 with a 1.59 ERA and did not give up a home run during the season.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Illness during the season reduced his starts.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He had his first of four 20-win seasons in 1905 as he ended the season with a 20–12 record and 2.01 ERA.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He finished with a career-high 132 strikeouts.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] In 1906 his 1.72 ERA was third in the league and he finished with a 21–9 record and tied a career-high with nine shutouts.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] To begin the 1907 season, Joss won his first 10 starts.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He threw two one-hitters during the season, the first on September 4 against the Detroit Tigers and the second on September 25 versus the New York Highlanders.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] When teammate Heinie Berger threw his own one-hitter on September 26, it marked just the second time since 1900 that two pitchers from the same team had thrown back-to-back one-hitters.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss finished the season with career-bests in wins (finished 27–11) and 338+2⁄3 innings pitched.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] His win total tied with Doc White for highest in the American League and his WHIP was second-best (behind Cy Young) while both his complete game (34) and shutout (6) totals were third-best in the league.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Before the 1908 season started, the Naps' home field, League Park, was expanded by about 4,000 seats.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] In what proved to be one of the tightest ever pitching duels in a perfect game, Joss took the mound for the Naps, while the White Sox pitcher was future Hall of Famer Ed Walsh.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Neither pitcher would give up an earned run in the 1–0 game.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Walsh, blistering through his own 39 win season, struck out 15 batters, gave up only one base on balls and allowed only four scattered hits by the Naps.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] The Naps' Joe Birmingham scored the team's only run, which came in the third inning—the lone, unearned run scored as a result of a botched pickoff play and a wild pitch.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] The tension in the ballpark was described by one writer as "a mouse working his way along the grandstand floor would have sounded like a shovel scraping over concrete." Joss, having faced the minimum 24 batters in the first eight innings, retired the first two batters in the top of the ninth.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss then faced White Sox pinch hitter John Anderson.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Anderson hit a line drive that could have resulted in a double had it not gone foul.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He then hit a ball to Naps third baseman Bill Bradley, which Bradley bobbled before throwing to first baseman George Stovall.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Stovall dug the ball out of the dirt to achieve the final out.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] With the win, Joss recorded the second ever perfect game in MLB's modern era.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He accomplished the feat with just 74 pitches, the lowest known pitch count ever achieved in a perfect game.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] After the game, Joss said, "I never could have done it without Larry Lajoie's and Stovall's fielding and without Birmingham's base running.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] For the season, Joss averaged 0.83 walks per nine innings, becoming one of 29 pitchers in MLB history to average less than one walk per nine innings.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] His season-ending WHIP of .806 is the fifth-lowest single-season mark in MLB history.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] The Naps finished with a 90–64 record, a half-game behind Detroit.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] It was the closest Joss ever got to a World Series appearance.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] After amassing four consecutive 20-win seasons, Joss struggled in 1909 as a result of fatigue; by September he was shut down for the season.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss finished the year with a 14–13 record in 242+2⁄3 innings pitched and recorded a 1.71 ERA.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He finished fourth in the American League in ERA and third in WHIP (.944).
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss pitched a second no-hitter, on April 20, 1910, against the White Sox, becoming the first pitcher in MLB history to no-hit the same team twice, a feat not matched until Tim Lincecum of the San Francisco Giants no-hit the San Diego Padres in both 2013 and 2014.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] In the second inning, the White Sox' Freddy Parent hit a ball toward third base.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Bill Bradley failed to field the ball cleanly and thus his throw to first base was not in time to get Parent out.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] The initial ruling on the field was a base hit but it was later changed to an error.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss gave up two walks and recorded 10 assists.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He made just 13 appearances that season due to a torn ligament in his right elbow.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss made his last appearance of the season on July 25, and left the game in the fifth inning due to arm soreness.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] In his final game, he allowed three runs on five hits and two walks with six strikeouts in a 4–0 loss.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] In his final major league season, Joss finished with a 5–5 record in 107+1⁄3 innings.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] This marked the fifth time in Joss' nine years that the franchise finished with a losing record.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Of Joss' 160 major league wins, 45 were shutouts.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss' 1.89 career ERA is ranked second all-time (to Ed Walsh), while his 0.97 WHIP (walks and hits per inning pitched) is the lowest career WHIP in MLB history.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He finished with a 160–97 record, 234 complete games, and 920 strikeouts.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss' repertoire included a fastball, a "slow ball" (today known as a changeup), and an "extremely effective" curve.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Baseball historians Rob Neyer and Bill James ranked Joss' fastball third (1900–1904) and sixth (1905–1909) in the major leagues.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] George Moriarty explained that Joss had only one curveball because "he believed that with a few well mastered deliveries he could acquire great control and success with less strain on his arm." In an era filled with spitball pitchers, Joss achieved his success without ever altering the baseball.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Illness and injury accompanied Joss throughout much of his professional career.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] In 1903, a high fever forced him to miss the last month of the season.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He contracted malaria in April 1904 and then missed several starts with a back injury in 1905.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss was concerned about supporting his family after his baseball career ended; many players of the day had little education and few marketable job skills beyond their abilities on the diamond.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] As sportswriter Franklin Lewis wrote, "Only a handful of players in the rough, stirring, early days of the major leagues arrived from campuses.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] And when they did, sometimes the shock was too great for them.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Some grizzled holdovers from the 1890s were around and they bore down heavily on the eardrums of the so-called college-boy set." Joss was hired as a sports columnist after the 1906 season for the *Toledo News-Bee*.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He also served as their Sunday sports editor.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] His writings proved so popular that sales of the paper increased and a special phone line was installed in his office to field the large volume of calls he received from fans.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] The increased popularity gave him an advantage when negotiating with the Naps before the 1907 season, and the club agreed to pay him $4,000 (equivalent to $138,000 in 2025).
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He later also wrote for the *Cleveland Press* and covered the World Series for the *News-Bee* and *Press* from 1907 to 1909.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] The *Press* introduced Joss in columns this way: "Of all the baseball players in the land, Addie Joss is far and away the best qualified for this work.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] During the 1908–1909 offseasons, Joss worked on designing an electric scoreboard that would later be known as the Joss Indicator.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] The Naps decided to install the scoreboard, which allowed spectators to monitor balls and strikes at League Park.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss attended spring training with Cleveland before the start of the 1911 season.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He collapsed on the field from heat prostration on April 3 in an exhibition game in Chattanooga, Tennessee.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He was taken to a local hospital and released the next day.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] As early as April 7, press reports had taken note of his ill health, but speculated about "ptomaine poisoning" or "nervous indigestion." The Naps traveled to Toledo for exhibition games on April 10 and Joss went to his home on Fulton Street where he was seen by his personal physician, Dr.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Chapman thought Joss could be suffering from nervous indigestion or food poisoning.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] By April 9, as Joss was coughing more and had a severe headache, Chapman changed his diagnosis to pleurisy and reported that Joss would not be able to play for one month and would need ten days of rest to recover.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss could not stand on his own and his speech was slurred.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss was well-liked by his peers and baseball fans.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Upon hearing of his death, the *Press* wrote "every train brings flowers" and "floral tributes by the wagonload are hourly arriving at the Joss home from all sections of the country." His family arranged for the funeral to take place on April 17.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] On that day, the Naps were to face the Detroit Tigers.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Naps players signed a petition stating that they would not attend the game so they could instead attend the funeral.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] They asked for the game to be rescheduled, but the Tigers balked at the request.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] American League president Ban Johnson initially supported the Tigers' position, but he ultimately sided with the Naps.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Naps owner Charles Somers and 15 Naps players attended the funeral, which was officiated by player-turned-evangelist Billy Sunday.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] The first "all-star" game was played as a benefit for Joss's family on July 24, 1911.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] The Naps invited players from the other seven American League teams to play against them.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Visiting club players who were involved in the game included Home Run Baker, Ty Cobb, Eddie Collins, Sam Crawford, Walter Johnson, Tris Speaker, Gabby Street, and Smoky Joe Wood.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] "I'll do anything they want for Addie Joss' family", Johnson said.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Washington Senators manager Jimmy McAleer volunteered to manage the all-stars.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] "The memory of Addie Joss is sacred to everyone with whom he ever came in contact.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] The man never wore a uniform who was a greater credit to the sport than he", McAleer said.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] The game was attended by approximately 15,270 fans and raised nearly $13,000 ($449,000 today) to help Joss' family members pay remaining medical bills.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] In 1981, Lawrence Ritter and Donald Honig included him in their book *The 100 Greatest Baseball Players of All Time.* They described what they called "the Smoky Joe Wood Syndrome", where a player of truly exceptional talent has a career curtailed by injury or illness.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] They argued that such a player should still be included among the greatest all-time players, in spite of career statistics that would not quantitatively rank him with the all-time greats.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] They believed that Joss' career ERA was proof enough of his greatness to be included.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] Joss was inducted into the Cleveland Guardians Hall of Fame on July 29, 2006.
[src:william-hulbert/addie-joss] He was inducted in the same class as Ray Chapman, Rocky Colavito, Al López, Sam McDowell, Al Rosen and Herb Score.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré made his MLB debut with the Dodgers in 1998 at age 19.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He led the majors with 48 home runs with the Dodgers in 2004, was the team MVP of the Red Sox in 2010, played in the 2011 World Series for the Rangers, and tied for the major league lead in hits in 2013.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On September 19, 2014, Beltré surpassed Vladimir Guerrero as the all-time MLB leader for hits by a Dominican player, a record since broken by Albert Pujols in 2019.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On July 30, 2017, Beltré became the 31st player in MLB history to reach 3,000 hits and the first Dominican player to achieve that milestone.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré retired following the 2018 season with 3,166 career hits (most by a third baseman in MLB history), 477 home runs, and 1,707 runs batted in.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He hit for the cycle three times in his career, in 2008, 2012, and 2015, one of five players to do so in MLB history, the others being Bob Meusel, Babe Herman, Trea Turner, and Christian Yelich.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Having played 21 major league seasons and won the Gold Glove Award five times, Beltré is notable for his defensive prowess and career longevity as well as his power hitting.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He played in four MLB All-Star Games and won the Silver Slugger Award four times.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Upon his retirement, Beltré was the only third baseman in history with both 3,000 career hits and 400 home runs.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] According to Baseball Reference, Beltré has the third-highest Wins Above Replacement among third basemen.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He retired as the all-time leader amongst third basemen in hits and RBIs, and ranked third in home runs amongst third basemen.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He is also the fifth major-leaguer to have hit at least 100 home runs for three different teams.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] In 2024, Beltré was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in his first year of eligibility.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré was born on April 7, 1979, in Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He attended Liceo Máximo Gómez High School.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] While working out at Campo Las Palmas in 1994, a Los Angeles Dodgers facility — one of the first of its kind for a Major League Baseball (MLB) team in the Dominican Republic — Beltré was spotted by scouts Ralph Avila and Pablo Peguero.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Though only 15 years old and weighing 130 lb (59 kg), Beltré featured a quick swing and live throwing arm.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On the insistence of Avila and Peguero, the Dodgers signed him in July 1994 with a $23,000 signing bonus.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré was a highly touted prospect when he began his major league career.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] After being called up to the majors from the then-Dodgers' Double-A affiliate San Antonio Missions, Beltré made his major league debut on June 24, 1998, starting at third base in the first game of an interleague series against the Anaheim Angels.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] At the time, he was the youngest player in the National League (NL).
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] During his first at-bat, Beltré hit a two-out run batted in (RBI) double off Angels starter Chuck Finley into left field to score Paul Konerko from second base to tie the game.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré hit his first home run six days later against Texas Rangers starter Rick Helling.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] At the end of the 1998 season, Beltré finished with 13 errors at third base while batting .215 with seven home runs.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] At one point in the spring training prior to the start of the 1999 season, Beltré's agent, Scott Boras, commented to him that "he couldn't believe" his relatively rapid ascent to the majors and handling of "such a difficult position like third base" at age 20.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré replied that he was 19 years old, not 20.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Boras then realized that Beltré's date of birth in the Dodgers' records was incorrect and indicated the same to the team, but, that if they were to correct the mistake by compensating Beltré for signing him at younger than MLB's allowable age, they would no longer pursue the issue.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Team personnel at Las Palmas denied Boras' assertion.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] As a result, Boras and Beltré went public.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Boras convinced MLB commissioner Bud Selig to investigate the Dodgers, and MLB suspended their scouting operations in the Dominican Republic for one year, as well as Avila and Peguero.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Dodgers general manager Fred Claire, whom MLB did not contact during their investigation, publicly expressed surprise and that he was unaware of the incident.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Selig awarded Beltré $48,500 in damages.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] In 2004, Beltré had a breakout season in which he established a number of career highs, including leading MLB with 48 home runs.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Other career highs included batting .334, 200 hits, 121 RBI, 104 runs scored, .629 slugging percentage, and a then-career high 32 doubles.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He finished second in voting for the NL Most Valuable Player Award (MVP) and was honored with his first career Silver Slugger Award and the Babe Ruth Home Run Award.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] The Seattle Mariners signed Beltré as a free agent before the 2005 season to a five-year, $64 million deal.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Regressing to his pre-2004 form, he batted just .255 with 19 home runs and 87 RBI.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Manager Mike Hargrove said after the season that he thought Beltré was personally disappointed in his first season in Seattle.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] After Beltré batted .167 through April 10, Ted Miller of the *Seattle Post-Intelligencer* wrote that he might become one of the Mariners' greatest busts.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He hit his first home run on April 29, raising his average to .198, and continued to improve his performance, batting .281 with 24 home runs the rest of the season.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On July 23, against the Boston Red Sox, Beltré hit an inside-the-park home run, the first one ever in Safeco Field history.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Though it was not a great season for Beltré, it was statistically his best as a Mariner.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He hit .276 and had 26 home runs, 99 RBI, and 41 doubles.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He also won a Fielding Bible Award for being the top MLB defensive third baseman during the year.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Despite many miscues, Beltré received recognition for his defense in 2007.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He tied with Brandon Inge for the AL lead in errors by a third baseman, with 18, but ranked second in the league in assists, total chances, and range factor.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He had the lowest fielding percentage of all third basemen in the league at .958.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] In spite of leading third basemen in errors, Beltré won his first Gold Glove Award, becoming the first Mariners third baseman to win the award.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He won his second consecutive Fielding Bible Award, as well.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On September 1, Beltré hit for the cycle, becoming the fourth Mariner to do so.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Arizona Diamondbacks shortstop Stephen Drew hit for the cycle that day as well, the first time two players had done so since 1920.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré's decision not to wear a cup despite playing third base has been well-documented.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] This came back to hurt him on August 12, 2009, when he took a hard ground ball to the groin.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Although he stayed in for the remainder of the 14-inning victory, he was put on the 15-day disabled list (DL) after suffering bleeding in one of his testicles.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] In his first game after returning from the DL, teammate Ken Griffey Jr. conspired with those responsible for the Safeco Field public address system to have Beltré's walk up music be the opening march from *The Nutcracker Suite*.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré declared free agency on November 5, 2009.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On January 7, 2010, Beltré signed a one-year, $9 million deal with the Boston Red Sox.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] The contract had a $5 million player option for 2011 with a $1 million buyout.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] While Beltré's career before coming to the Red Sox had been regarded as somewhat disappointing, he hit .321 with 28 homers and 49 doubles in 2010, benefiting from the hitter-friendly Fenway Park.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré led the Red Sox in batting average and tied David Ortiz for the team lead in RBIs (102).
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré led the Majors in doubles with 49 (also a career-high).
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He also finished fourth in the AL in batting average, and was fifth in the AL in total bases (326) and slugging percentage (.553).
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He also had two stolen bases on the year, and finished ninth in the MVP voting.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On January 5, 2011, Beltré signed a five-year, $80 million contract with the Texas Rangers.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He played with the Rangers for eight years until his retirement in 2018.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré's statistics improved when he was in his thirties.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] While he had previously played in pitcher-friendly ballparks in Los Angeles and Seattle, the Rangers' ballpark was known as a hitter-friendly environment.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] *The Wall Street Journal* described Beltré's Rangers tenure as "nothing short of brilliant".
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré was on the 2011 American League All-Star team.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On July 22, Beltré strained his hamstring and was also placed on the DL.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On September 4, he singled to right for his 2,000th career hit.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On September 11, Beltré hit two home runs, including the 300th of his career, against the Oakland Athletics.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He was named the AL Player of the Month for September.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] In 2011, Beltré batted .296 with 32 home runs, fifth in the AL.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He was third in the American League in slugging percentage (.561), sixth in RBIs (105), and ninth in OPS (.892).
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] The Fielding Bible said he saved 17 runs on defense in 2011.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On October 4, in Game 4 of the ALDS against the Tampa Bay Rays, Beltré became the sixth player to hit three home runs in a playoff game and the first do so in a Division Series.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré played in the World Series with the Rangers.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He added a fourth playoff home run in Game 5 of the World Series when he went down to one knee chasing an outside curve ball from Chris Carpenter.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Louis Cardinals defeated the Rangers in seven games.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] More recognition was bestowed on Beltré for his defense.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On November 1, he was honored with his third Gold Glove Award and first by a Ranger third baseman since Buddy Bell's six-year run from 1979 to 1984.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He also won his third Fielding Bible Award.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On November 2, he was awarded the Silver Slugger Award.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré was once again voted on to the All-Star Game starter, along with teammates Josh Hamilton and Mike Napoli.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] It was Beltré's third consecutive All-Star Game and the third of his career.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On August 22, against the Baltimore Orioles, Beltré hit three home runs in his first three at-bats, including two in the same inning.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He joined Pablo Sandoval, Albert Pujols, George Brett, Reggie Jackson, and Babe Ruth as the only players to hit a three-homer game in both the regular season and the postseason.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On August 24, he hit for the cycle for the second time in his career.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Both of his cycles came at Rangers Ballpark.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] With his first coming as a member of the Mariners, it was the first time in MLB history that a player had hit for the cycle more than once at the same stadium.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He joined Joe DiMaggio as the only players in big league history to have a three-homer game and a cycle in the same week.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] For his efforts, Beltré was named the AL Player of the Week for August 20–26.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] During the week, he hit .433 (13-for-30) with three doubles, one triple, five home runs, nine RBI, and seven runs scored.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He had the highest slugging percentage (1.100) in the majors, the most total bases (33), was tied for first in hits and home runs, and tied for second in RBI.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] After the season, Beltré won more defensive accolades.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He won his second consecutive Fielding Bible Award and fourth overall.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He was won a Gold Glove Award and his second Platinum Glove Award.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Wilson Sporting Goods honored him as one of their Defensive Players of the Year in the first year of that award.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] The Rangers organization named Beltré the team captain in 2013.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré was named the AL Player of the Week for July 1–7.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He batted .478 (11-for-23) with four home runs, two doubles and five RBI in six games.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He led the American League in home runs, slugging (1.087), OPS (1.607), total bases (25), and extra-base hits (six) while producing the fourth-highest batting average.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré hit safely in all six games with two or more hits four times.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He had the 24th multi-homer game of his career with a pair of home runs on July 4 against Seattle.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Maintaining his strong hitting throughout July, Beltré was named the AL Player of the Month, his fourth career monthly award.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He batted .369 with four doubles, nine homers, 19 RBI, and 13 runs scored over 26 games.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He tied for the major league monthly lead in home runs with Alfonso Soriano and total bases with Torii Hunter (69).
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré also was among the AL leaders in slugging percentage (second, .670), hits (tied for second, 38), extra-base hits (tied for fourth, 13), RBI (tied for fifth) and batting average (sixth).
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He capped off the month with a walk-off home run to lead the Rangers past the Angels on July 31, the seventh walk-off home run of his career and first with Texas.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] It was his third monthly award with Texas, making him one of seven players to win multiple times with the Rangers, including Josh Hamilton (four), Rafael Palmeiro, Alex Rodriguez (both with three), Iván Rodríguez, Juan González and Rubén Sierra (two each).
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] For the season, Beltré played in 161 games and totaled a .315 average, 30 homers, 92 RBI and .509 slugging percentage.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He led the AL with 199 hits and was fourth in batting average and fifth in total bases (321).
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He also made the top-10 in games played, slugging percentage and home runs.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] In the AL MVP voting, he was tied for seventh place.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] The Dallas-Fort Worth chapter of the Baseball Writers' Association of America named Beltré the Texas Rangers Player of the Year.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On May 7, while facing Jorge de la Rosa of the Colorado Rockies, Beltré hit his 100th home run as a member of the Rangers, becoming the fifth player in major league history to hit 100 home runs with three teams, following Darrell Evans, Reggie Jackson, Alex Rodriguez, and Jim Thome.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On June 24, Beltré singled off Drew Smyly of the Detroit Tigers for his 2,500th career hit and the first hit of a 4-for-4 game.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On September 18, Beltré singled off Sonny Gray in the first inning for his 2,591st hit, surpassing Vladimir Guerrero as the all-time hit leader among Dominican-born players.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré finished the 2014 season batting .324, his highest average since 2004, with 19 home runs and 77 RBI in 148 games.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] In February, the Rangers picked up Beltré's option, which would have become guaranteed if he had reached 586 plate appearances in the 2015 season.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] While playing against Cleveland on May 15, Beltré hit his 400th home run on a sinker from Bruce Chen.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He became the 52nd player in MLB history to reach that plateau, and the fourth to do so while playing at least 75 percent of his games at third base.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On August 3, Beltré hit for the cycle with hits in each of the first, second, third, and fifth innings at home against the Houston Astros in a 12–9 win.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] It was his third career cycle, second as a Ranger, and third at the Rangers' home park, making him the only player ever to hit three cycles in one stadium.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He became the first Rangers player to hit for multiple cycles.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] The first player in 82 years to hit for a third cycle, he became the fourth player to do so and tied the major league record for total career cycles, joining Long John Reilly, Bob Meusel, and Babe Herman.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] During the last week of the season, and the Rangers' run towards the AL West championship, Beltré batted .448 with two home runs and 13 RBI.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He also went 2-for-4 with a home in the final game of the season to help the Rangers advance to their sixth AL West title.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He finished the season with 18 home runs, 83 RBI, 163 hits, and .287 average.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Enduring a torn ligament in his left thumb over the last three months of the season, Beltré had surgery to repair it immediately after the season ended.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] The Phi Delta Theta fraternity presented Beltré with the 2014 Lou Gehrig Memorial Award on September 17, 2015, making him the first Rangers player to win the award.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On April 15, Beltré and the Rangers agreed to a two-year, $36 million contract extension that would last through the 2018 seasons.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] The extension prevented Beltré from becoming a free agent at the end of the season.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Displaying a drop to one knee, Beltré hit a home run on a curve ball from Jesse Hahn of Oakland on May 17.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] In a May 29 game against the Pittsburgh Pirates, Beltré hit a two-run home run off Juan Nicasio to give him 1,501 career RBI, making him the 54th player to reach the milestone and the fourth third baseman.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On July 2, Beltré became the 28th player all time to amass 10,000 career at-bats.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On July 23, he became the 36th player all time to record 11,000 career plate appearances.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Two days later, he hit a walk-off home run, the ninth of his career, against the Athletics in the bottom of the ninth inning for a 7−6 win.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On August 24, Beltré, in a game against the Cincinnati Reds, hit a go-ahead two-out double for his 2,900th career hit and led the Rangers to a 6–5 win.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] With this hit, Beltré became the 39th player in major league history to reach the milestone.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré would once again show his signature home run knee drop after hitting a solo shot in the second inning in a game against the Houston Astros on September 13.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] His 30th of the season, it was the first time he reached the mark since 2013 and fifth in his career.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Ten days later, his two-run home run in the eighth inning against the Athletics aided the Rangers in clinching the AL West division crown for the second year in a row and the seventh in franchise history.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He also reached 100 RBI for the first time since 2012 and fifth time in his career.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He won the Gold Glove at third base, the fifth of his career.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré began the 2017 season on the 10-day disabled list after injuring his right leg near the end of spring training.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On July 4, Beltré hit his 600th career double, becoming the 17th player all-time to reach that milestone.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On July 7, Beltré became the 21st player to amass 5,000 career total bases.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On July 26, Beltré was ejected by umpire Gerry Davis; in a game against the Miami Marlins, Davis asked Beltré, who was the next scheduled batter, to move closer to the on-deck circle.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré responded by picking up the edge of the logo that marked the on-deck circle and moving it closer to where he had been standing, which prompted Davis to eject him.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré collected his 3,000th hit with a double into left field against Wade Miley of the Baltimore Orioles on July 30, making him the 31st player to reach this milestone and the first Dominican-born player to accomplish it.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré played in only 94 games in 2017 due to hamstring and calf problems.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Prior to the start of the 2018 season, the Rangers signed Bartolo Colón, giving them the only two active players with at least 20 seasons in the major leagues and the last two active players to have played in 1990s.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On April 5, Beltré doubled in the second inning versus the Oakland Athletics to pass Rod Carew as the all-time Latin American hits leader.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On June 13, Beltré hit a double that gave him 3,090 career hits; this made him the all-time leader in hits by a player not born in the United States, surpassing former Mariners teammate Ichiro Suzuki.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On November 20, 2018, Beltré announced his retirement.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] In 2,933 games over 21 seasons, Beltré posted a .286 batting average with 3,166 hits, 477 home runs, 1,707 RBI, 121 stolen bases, 1,524 runs, 636 doubles, a .339 on-base percentage, a .480 slugging percentage, and a .960 fielding percentage.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] In 28 postseason games, he hit .261 with five home runs and 11 RBI.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré is regarded as one of the greatest third basemen of all time.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Having played 21 major league seasons and won five Gold Gloves, he was notable for his longevity, fielding ability, and power hitting.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré's signature home run swing included a drop to one knee when connecting with a breaking ball, particularly notable during Game 5 of the 2011 World Series against Cardinals ace Chris Carpenter.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré's defensive style was somewhat unorthodox.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Rangers manager Ron Washington remarked that Beltré fielded ground balls incorrectly by stopping before catching the ball and relying very little on the positioning of his feet in throwing the ball to first base.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré explained that his arm was so strong that early in his career he was making many throwing errors; by planting his feet, he was able to improve his accuracy despite his lack of proper foot positioning.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Another major league manager, Joe Maddon, compared the unique style of Beltré's defensive play to Ozzie Smith's "flair at shortstop", Stan Musial's "coiled batting stance", and the way Steve Carlton wrapped his left wrist before releasing a slider.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Commented Maddon further on Beltré's defense, "There's a lot of guys that did things unique to them that weren't out of the *Spalding Guide*.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He's a super smart player, knows where to position himself." Beltré was known for the sense of playfulness and joy that he exhibited on the field.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He had a routine with Rangers shortstop Elvis Andrus on pop flies where both men put their arms up to catch the ball.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] During a game against the Red Sox on June 26, 2016, Sandy León hit a foul ball which landed in the first row in the stands, just out of Beltré's reach.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] However, instead of returning immediately to the infield, he reached very close to the ball in a motion, pretending as if he were going to take it away from the fan who caught León's foul ball.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] As a hitter, Beltré also regularly pointed to the first base umpire to appeal a checked swing, a move usually only done by catchers.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré also had a joking relationship with Mariners pitcher Felix Hernández, which included Beltré getting ejected in 2010, when the two former teammates first faced each other, and Hernández hugging Beltré on the field in 2017, the day after Beltré's 3,000th major league hit.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré was also known for his dislike of anyone touching the top of his head.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Before the game where he recorded his 3,000th hit, he let his teammates touch his head.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Much to his dismay, the act turned into a game, inducing repeat offenders, including Andrus.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] After a game in which he hit a grand slam that provided the decisive runs in a 5–2 win over the Athletics on August 15, 2016, he took a broom from the groundskeepers closet and began combing an area of infield dirt.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Still, Rougned Odor trotted to Beltré carrying a full drink bucket but missed drenching Beltré when he threw the blue sports drink at his teammate.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré played for the Dominican Republic in the 2006 World Baseball Classic (WBC).
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He was named to the All-WBC team after hitting 4 home runs in six games.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He also played in the 2017 WBC, batting 1-for-15 in four games.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] In 2017, he was dealing with leg injuries that caused him to miss the beginning of the MLB season.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré was one of several Dominican Hall of Famers assisting general manager Nelson Cruz ahead of the 2026 WBC.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] On June 5, 2023, Beltré was named the honorary general manager for the Karachi Monarchs of the Baseball United league for their inaugural season.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré served as the manager for the American League team in the 2024 All-Star Futures Game.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré has contributed to humanitarian activities in the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex such as the Texas Rangers Baseball Foundation, Texas Rangers RBI program, the I Love Baseball program, which operates in the Dominican Republic, and the Baseball Tomorrow Fund.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] He has donated to Dave Valle's Esperanza International as well as foundations established by other major-league players, including Robinson Chirinos, Eddie Guardado, Joakim Soria, and Michael Young.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] In 2021, Beltré helped pay to reconstruct a baseball stadium in the Dominican Republic where he grew up playing.
[src:william-hulbert/adrián-beltré] Beltré and his wife have three children.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] Born in Burlington Flats, New York, Hulbert moved with his family to Chicago two years later where he lived the rest of his life save for a stint at Beloit College beginning in 1867.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] When he returned to Chicago from school, he married into the family of a successful grocer and expanded the business into the coal trade.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] A backer of the Chicago White Stockings baseball club of the National Association from its inception in 1871, Hulbert became an officer of the club in 1874 when it resumed play after being forced to sit out two seasons due to the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] He assumed the club presidency the next year.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] In his brief tenure as a club president in the National Association, Hulbert soon became fed up with the circuit's lack of definite structure, organization, and integrity.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] He was particularly disgusted by the Davy Force case in 1874.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] Force, the shortstop of the White Stockings that year, was a notorious "contract jumper", a common occurrence in the National Association in which players would move from team to team each year selling themselves to the highest bidder.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] Determined to keep his shortstop, Hulbert signed him to a contract for the 1875 season in September, before the 1874 season had concluded, a violation of league rules.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] In December, Force signed a second contract with the Philadelphia Athletics, and Hulbert protested.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] The Association Judiciary committee originally awarded Force to Chicago, but at a second meeting in early 1875, after a Philadelphia man had been elected president of the association, the decision was reversed.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] Hulbert became convinced that the Eastern ballclubs were conspiring to keep the Western clubs second-class citizens and plotted to overthrow the might of the Boston Red Stockings, which won each association pennant between 1872 and 1875.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] To do so, he convinced Illinois native and star Boston pitcher Al Spalding to sign with Chicago for the 1876 season and also signed Boston stars Cal McVey, Deacon White, and Ross Barnes and Philadelphia stars Cap Anson and Ezra Sutton, though Sutton later backed out of his deal.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] The signings were made while the 1875 season was in progress, but Hulbert decided to anticipate league disciplinary action by establishing his own league.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] After enlisting the support of Western clubs including the Cincinnati Red Stockings, the St.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] The result was the founding of the National League of Professional Baseball Clubs.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] At the founding meeting, straws were drawn to determine the first president of the circuit, and Hartford president Morgan Bulkeley drew the short straw.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] He only remained president for one year and took little interest in the affairs of the league, not even bothering to attend the 1877 league meeting.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] When he did not show up, Hulbert was elected the new president, retaining his presidency of the White Stockings as well.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] In his tenure as president from 1877 to his death in 1882, Hulbert ruled with an iron fist and took steps to ensure league integrity and compliance with league rules.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] His first major act was expelling the New York and Philadelphia clubs from the league for failure to complete their 1876 schedules as required.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] While losing clubs in the two most populous cities in the United States was a serious blow, the expulsion sent a clear message that the lax adherence to league rules that had plagued the National Association would not be tolerated.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] Also in response to the New York/Philadelphia scheduling problem, Hulbert ended the practice of clubs determining their schedules through the club secretaries by declaring that the league itself would establish the schedule.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] Hulbert also instituted the practice of the league hiring of umpires to bolster public perceptions of league integrity.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] Perhaps his greatest challenge was dealing with four members of the Louisville ball club who conspired to throw the 1877 pennant.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] In a move that established a precedent for future handling of dishonest ballplayers, Hulbert banned all four players from the league for life.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] The banning had a ripple effect across the league that led to the Louisville, St.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] Louis, and Hartford franchises folding, and the league began to face a crisis as Hulbert was forced to replace these and other teams over the years with clubs from smaller cities such as Providence, Indianapolis, Milwaukee, and Syracuse.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] Hulbert's final major act as president also involved the Cincinnati franchise.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] This led the league to pass new rules banning both for the 1881 season and then expelling the unapologetic Cincinnati club for violating a rule that would not go into effect for two more months.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] This final league expulsion brought the National League its greatest challenge yet, as Cincinnati spearheaded the creation of the rival American Association in 1882 that moved into populous areas abandoned by the NL over the years such as New York and Philadelphia.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] Hulbert did not live to see this rival franchise begin play, however, dying of a heart attack in 1882 at the age of 49 two weeks before the AA made its debut.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] For decades, Hulbert was kept out of the Baseball Hall of Fame despite his critical role in founding the first professional league.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] The Veterans Committee finally enshrined Hulbert in 1995.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] Hulbert is buried in Graceland Cemetery under a grave marker designed to look like a baseball.
[src:william-hulbert/william-hulbert] In addition to his name and his birth and death dates, the marker includes the names of the cities that were in the National League at the time of his death.
